\c 1
\p
\v 1 \add The following\add* are the words of the leader,\f + \fr 1:1 \ft We don’t have enough information to fully understand the meaning of the Hebrew word ‘קֹהֶ֣לֶת’ (Kohelet), but it probably means something like ‘leader/speaker of the assembly’, so we use ‘the leader’ throughout this document.\f* David’s son, king in Yerushalem \add (Jerusalem)\add*:
\s1 Everything’s meaningless
\q1
\v 2 “Totally pointless,” says the leader.
\q1 “\add A complete waste of time\add*. Everything’s worthless.”
\q1
\v 3 What profit does humanity gain from all \add their hard work in this world\add*?
\q1
\v 4 \add Generations come, and generations go\add*,
\q1 \add but the world just carries on going\add*.
\q1
\v 5 The sun rises and the sun sets,
\q1 then \add rushes\add* \add around\add* to its place, rising there \add again\add*.
\q1
\v 6 Going to the south then around to the north,
\q1 the wind is going, changing, turning,
\q1 then \add it’s\add* returning on its rounds.
\q1
\v 7 All the rivers \add flow into\add* the sea \add but it never gets\add* full.
\q1 The place that the rivers are going to, they \add end up\add* going \add there\add* again.
\q1
\v 8 Everything is wearisome—\add not even worth talking about\add*.
\q1 The \add eyes\add* \add never stop\add* seeing,
\q1 and \add your\add* \add ears\add* \add never fill up with everything they hear\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Whatever that was \add in the past\add*, it will be \add in the future\add*,
\q1 and \add everything that’s happened before, will happen\add* \add again\add*.
\q1 There’s nothing new \add in this world\add*.
\q1
\v 10 If someone says, “Look at this—it’s new,”
\q1 \add well\add*, it was already done \add long ago before we even got here\add*.
\q1
\v 11 \add Things that happened in the past get forgotten\add*,
\q1 and \add the same will also happen for future events\add*.
\q1 \add People in the future will be exactly the same\add*.
\s1 The persecution of wise
\q1
\v 12 I, the leader, was king over Yisrael in Yerushalem.
\q1
\v 13 I \add used my mind and\add* wisdom to discover and to explore everything that is done \add in this world\add*.
\q1 It’s a difficult job that God has given humanity to be busy with.
\q1
\v 14 I saw all the deeds that are done \add in this world\add*,
\q1 and look—everything’s pointless \add like\add* chasing after the wind.
\q1
\v 15 Something that’s bent can’t be straightened \add again\add*,
\q1 and what’s missing can’t be counted.
\q1
\v 16 I spoke with \add sincerity\add*, saying, “Look at me—I’ve become \add powerful\add*,
\q1 and I’ve \add increased in wisdom relative to everyone who ruled before me\add* \add here\add* in Yerushalem.\x + \xo 1:16: \xt 1Ki 4:29-31.\x*
\q1 \add My mind has acquired\add* much knowledge and wisdom.”
\q1
\v 17 I \add made it my aim to discover\add* knowledge and wisdom \add versus\add* madness and folly.
\q1 I was aware that that also is chasing after the wind
\q1
\v 18 because \add having much wisdom leads to much frustration\add*
\q1 and anyone who’s adding knowledge is \add also\add* adding pain.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 I said \add to myself\add*,
\q1 “Come on, let me \add find out what’s good and enjoy the pleasure from them\add*.”
\q1 But look, it was also pointless.
\q1
\v 2 To laughter, I said, “It’s madness,”
\q1 and to joy, “What’s \add the point of this\add*?”
\q1
\v 3 I explored in myself how to \add indulge my body\add* with wine, but my \add mind\add* was guiding me in wisdom.
\q1 \add Also,\add* how to grasp foolishness
\q1 until I could see whether that’s better for humanity to do \add while they live out their lives here on this earth\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 4 I expanded my \add program of works\add*.
\q1 I built houses for myself.
\q1 I planted vineyards for myself.\x + \xo 2:4-8: \xt 1Ki 10:23-27; 2Ch 9:22-27.\x*
\q1
\v 5 I made gardens for myself, and royal parks,
\q1 and I planted \add all different kinds\add* of fruit trees in them.
\q1
\v 6 I constructed pools for myself
\q1 to \add irrigate\add* a forest of growing trees.
\q1
\v 7 I acquired male and female servants,
\q1 and \add the children born to them\add* belonged to me.
\q1 Also \add a large number\add* of sheep and cattle belonged to me—
\q1 more than all \add my predecessors\add* in Yerushalem.\x + \xo 2:7: \xt 1Ki 4:23.\x*
\q1
